   "source": [
    "## 1. Introduction\n",
    "\n",
    "Inventory management is a key business problem in retail and supply chain operations. \n",
    "The classical Economic Order Quantity (EOQ) model assumes that demand is constant and known in advance. \n",
    "In real business environments, demand changes over time and may be affected by seasonality, holidays, and customer behavior.\n",
    "\n",
    "The goal of this project is to extend the classical EOQ model by using data-driven demand forecasting. \n",
    "Historical retail sales data will be analyzed and used to estimate future demand. \n",
    "The forecasted demand will then be used as input for an adaptive EOQ model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "33b373c1-7915-4493-91f2-43bb889f259c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Project Objectives\n",
    "\n",
    "The main objectives of this project are:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Analyze historical retail sales data\n",
    "- Combine sales data with external holiday information\n",
    "- Build a demand forecasting model\n",
    "- Compare a baseline forecast with a machine learning model\n",
    "- Use forecasted demand in an adaptive EOQ model\n",
    "- Evaluate how data-driven demand planning can improve inventory decisions"
   ]
  },
  {
